        "text": "Isaiah 51:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; that of the flower, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 14:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". אנושׁ is man as a mortal being; his life's duration is likened to that of a blade of grass, and his beauty and glory to a flower of the field, whose fullest bloom is also the beginning of its fading. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 103:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " בּו (the same as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 40:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) refers to man, who is compared to grass and flowers. כּי is ἐάν with a hypothetical perfect; and the wind that scorches up the plants, referred to man, is an emblem of every form of peril that threatens life: often enough it is really a breath of wind which snaps off a man's life. The bold designation of vanishing away without leaving any trace, \"and his place knoweth him no more,\" is taken from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 7:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ibid. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 20:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In the midst of this plant-like, frail destiny, there is, however, one strong ground of comfort. There is an everlasting power, which raises all those who link themselves with it above the transitoriness involved in nature's laws, and makes them eternal like itself. This power is the mercy of God, which spans itself above (על) all those who fear Him like an eternal heaven. This is God's righteousness, which rewards faithful adherence to His covenant and conscientious fulfilment of His precepts in accordance with the order of redemption, and shows itself even to (ל) children's children, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 20:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 34:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : on into a thousand generations, i.e., into infinity. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
